83rd OREGON LEGISLATIVE ASSEMBLY--2026 Regular Session
A-Engrossed
Senate Bill 1570
Ordered by the Senate February 20
Including Senate Amendments dated February 20
Sponsored by Senator CAMPOS, Representatives GRAYBER, RUIZ, Senators BROADMAN, GELSER BLOUIN,
GORSEK, PATTERSON, REYNOLDS, Representatives CHAICHI, RIEKE SMITH; Senators FREDERICK,
GOLDEN, MANNING JR, NERON MISSLIN, PHAM K, PROZANSKI, Representatives GAMBA, SOSA,
WALTERS, WISE (at the request of Oregon Nurses Association) (Presession filed.)
SUMMARY
The following summary is not prepared by the sponsors of the measure and is not a part of the body thereof subject
to consideration by the Legislative Assembly. It is an editor’s brief statement of the essential features of the
measure. The statement includes a measure digest written in compliance with applicable readability standards.
Digest: Limits when a hospital may share certain info. Tells a hospital to assign which
areas of the hospital are not open to the public. (Flesch Readability Score: 64.2).
[Digest: The Act tells OHA to do a study about health care facilities. (Flesch Readability Score:
67.7).]
[Requires the Oregon Health Authority to study protections in health care facilities. Directs the
authority to submit findings to the interim committees of the Legislative Assembly related to health no
later than September 15, 2027.]
[Sunsets on January 2, 2028.]
Prohibits a hospital from disclosing for purposes of law enforcement individually iden-
tifiable health information or information concerning a person’s citizenship or immigration
status unless disclosure is required by state or federal law or court order or for ensuring
continuity of care. Requires a hospital to designate which areas of the hospital are not open
to the public.
Makes it an unlawful employment practice for a hospital or federally qualified health
center to retaliate or take disciplinary action against an employee for distributing informa-
tional or educational materials concerning immigration rights and legal services. Allows an
employee alleging a violation to file a complaint with the Bureau of Labor and Industries.
Requires hospitals and federally qualified health centers to treat information concerning
a person’s citizenship or immigration status or a person’s country of birth in the same
manner as protected health information.
Takes effect on the 91st day following adjournment sine die.
1 A BILL FOR AN ACT
2 Relating to protections in health care facilities; and prescribing an effective date.
3 Be It Enacted by the People of the State of Oregon:
4 SECTION 1. (1) As used in this section:
5 (a) “Hospital” has the meaning given that term in ORS 442.015.
6 (b) “Individually identifiable health information” has the meaning given that term in ORS
7 192.556.
8 (c) “Information concerning a person’s citizenship or immigration status” has the
9 meaning given that term in ORS 180.805.
10 (d) “Law enforcement authority” includes a federal, state and local law enforcement au-
11 thority.
12 (2) A hospital shall designate which areas of the hospital are not open to the
13 public. Areas designated as not open to the public must include any area:
14 (a) Where entry or access to the area is controlled; or
15 (b) That is a patient room.
NOTE: Matter in boldfaced type in an amended section is new; matter [italic and bracketed] is existing law to be omitted.
New sections are in boldfaced type.
LC 290

A-Eng. SB 1570
1 (3) A hospital may not disclose for the purpose of law enforcement individually identifi-
2 able health information or information concerning a person’s citizenship or immigration
3 status unless disclosure is:
4 (a) Required by state or federal law or an order of a court of competent jurisdiction, in-
5 cluding a judicial warrant; or
6 (b) For the purpose of ensuring continuity of care.
7 (4) A hospital shall adopt and maintain written policies and procedures that:
8 (a) Address how the hospital will respond if a law enforcement authority arrives at the
9 hospital; and
10 (b) Identify for the hospital at least one administrator in a supervisory role who is des-
11 ignated to respond when a law enforcement authority arrives at the hospital.
12 SECTION 2. (1) As used in this section, “health care facility” means:
13 (a) A hospital as defined in ORS 442.015.
14 (b) A federally qualified health center as defined in 42 U.S.C. 1396d(l)(2).
15 (2) It is an unlawful employment practice for a health care facility to retaliate or take
16 disciplinary action against an employee of the health care facility because the employee has
17 distributed informational or educational materials concerning immigrant rights and available
18 immigration legal services if the materials are published or otherwise made available by a
19 state agency.
20 (3) An employee who alleges a violation of this section may file a complaint with the
21 Commissioner of the Bureau of Labor and Industries in the manner provided by ORS
22 659A.820.
23 (4) Nothing in this section prohibits a collective bargaining agreement from establishing
24 terms that are more protective than the requirements under this section.
25 SECTION 3. Section 4 of this 2026 Act is added to and made a part of ORS 192.553 to
26 192.581.
27 SECTION 4. (1) As used in this section:
28 (a) “Health care facility” means:
29 (A) A hospital as defined in ORS 442.015.
30 (B) A federally qualified health center as defined in 42 U.S.C. 1396d(l)(2).
31 (b) “Information concerning a person’s citizenship or immigration status” has the
32 meaning given that term in ORS 180.805.
33 (2) A health care provider that is a health care facility shall treat information concerning
34 a person’s citizenship or immigration status or a person’s country of birth in the same
35 manner that the health care provider is required to treat protected health information under
36 state law.
37 SECTION 5. This 2026 Act takes effect on the 91st day after the date on which the 2026
38 regular session of the Eighty-third Legislative Assembly adjourns sine die.
